article.headline: Thorn goes 8-for-11 from 3-point range for Cougars
article.linkText: Battling sickness, Thorn lights it up for No. 22 BYU
article.story:
CEDAR CITY, Utah (AP) -- Brigham Young guard Erin Thorn was
fighting a cold and played only eight minutes in the second half,
but her first half was enough.

	   Thorn shot 7-for-8 from 3-point range in the first half alone to
lead BYU (4-0; No. 22 ESPN/USA Today; No. 19 Associated Press) to a 75-44 victory over Southern Utah (2-1)
Tuesday night.

	   ''I'm sick and I was just trying to do whatever I could,'' Thorn
said. ''To have a half like that while your sick is awesome.''

	   Thorn added another 3 in the second half, finishing 8-for-11 on
3-point shots, which accounted for all of her 24 points.

	   ''That's the kind of player she is,'' BYU coach Jeff Judkins
said. ''She can really shoot the ball. When she gets open like
that, usually she can make it.''

	   Thorn had 21 of BYU's 41 first-half points.

	   In all, the Cougars hit nine of their 13 3-point shots in the
first half, as they built a 41-27 halftime lead.

	   Thorn said BYU's motion offense led to open shots for the
Cougars, allowing them to convert from 3-point range.

	   ''We just ran our motion and got good screens,'' Thorn said.
''Our movement gets it open because they can't stay with you the
whole 30 seconds.''

	   BYU's defense stifled the Thunderbirds, who shot only 27 percent
from the field for the game.

	   The Cougars extended their lead to 31 points, 75-44, and the
Thunderbirds (2-1) never got closer than 16 points in the second
half.

	   Casey Cooke and Lacey Yates each scored 10 points for Southern
Utah.

	   Jennifer Leitner had 11 rebounds for the Cougars, who finished
with a 46-38 advantage in rebounds.

	   The teams combined for 43 turnovers, 25 by BYU. Southern Utah
shot 27 percent from the field.
